From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0017/N] copy_bsd_aarch64.S: stub the whole file out under CHERI

The 240-line aarch64 assembly file uses non-cap `ldr/str/ldp/stp` with
`[xN]`-style operands; the purecap assembler rejects every one of
them as "invalid operand for instruction". A full cap-aware rewrite
of the copy routines is Phase 2 work (it requires deciding tag-
preservation policy for oop arrays).

For Phase 1 ("make it build") the simplest path is to make the
entire file empty under `__CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__`. The .hpp's
`pd_*` callers are patched in 0018 to short-circuit to `memcpy`/
`memmove` under CHERI, so the `_Copy_*` extern symbols this file
would normally provide are never referenced — the linker doesn't
complain about missing definitions.

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md §6 (patch 0017)

--- a/src/hotspot/os_cpu/bsd_aarch64/copy_bsd_aarch64.S
+++ b/src/hotspot/os_cpu/bsd_aarch64/copy_bsd_aarch64.S
@@ -23,6 +23,13 @@
  *
  */

+#ifndef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+// stopless-java-gc: the asm below uses non-cap aarch64 ldr/str/ldp/stp
+// with [%[s]] operands that the purecap assembler rejects. Stub the
+// whole file out for CHERI; the .hpp's pd_* functions short-circuit to
+// memcpy under __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__ so no _Copy_* symbol is
+// referenced and the linker stays happy.
+
 #define CFUNC(x) _##x

         .global CFUNC(_Copy_conjoint_words)
@@ -238,3 +245,5 @@ bwd_copy_drain:
         .align  5
 0:
         ret
+
+#endif // !__CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
